fpow=
fphead2="WARNING: Since we have no control over equipment or data which may be used with this program, no responsibility is implied or assumed"
fphead3="for results obtained through its use. The user must assume the entire risk of using program and computed results."
fphead4=" **** TRAJECTORY TABLE calculated by Exterior Ballistics Program ****"
fphead5="Calculations according to " 
fphead6=" - Drag Function"

fpower1="Velocity at impact"
fpower2="(The author provides these formulas only as a source of comparative and historical information. The user may decide himself about the usefulness of such formulas.) "
fpower3="For handgun bullets. Described by Col. Julian S. Hatcher in : Pistols and Revolvers and Their Use, 1927, possibly inspired by the Thompson-LaGarde experiments (1904), trying to shoot 13 cattle with handguns. The short form RSP and the velocity modified RSP are calculated. Formula: (shapefactor * area * velocity * weight / 1000)."
fpower4=" Hatcher's RSP: Sectional Density of the bullet is too low for adaequate penetration. The calculated effect on target is too high."
fpower5=" A Hatcher's RSP of less than 15 is inadequate for defensive work. 15 to 17 are considered adequate, above 17 seems to be excellent. "
fpower6=" According to The A-Square Handloading and Rifle Manual -Any Shot You Want-. Formula: (.01 * energy * sectional density / area)."
fpower7= " According to The A-Square Handloading and Rifle Manual -Any Shot You Want-, identical to Josserand Enery Transfer Function. Formula: (energy * area)."
fpower8=" Described in Mel Tappan's book -Survival Guns-, formula similar to Hatcher's RSP."
fpower9= "Muzzle velocity"
fpower10= " The IPSC Power Factor is used to determine MAYOR or MINOR caliber. Loads with a factor over 175 is rated MAJOR. Between 125 and 175 are rated as MINOR caliber. A power factor of less than 125 is not allowed for IPSC competition. Formula: (weight * velocity / 1000)."
fpower11=" Lott's Estimated Effective Energy "
fpower12=" Sometimes also called Lott's Power Factor. EEE1: Penetration factor for conventional soft point bullets, published by Jack Lott in: Big Bore Rifles, G&A Action Series, 1983. Formula: (Diameter * Sectional Density * Muzzle Energy). EEE2: Penetration factor for bullets capable of controlled expansion and high weight retention at high impact velocities. Formula: (Diameter * Muzzle Energy)."
fpower13=" Penetration value suitable for solid or FMJ bullets. Desribed in the book: African Rifles and Cartridges, 1948, by John Taylor. Formula: (diameter * weight * velocity) / 7000."
fpower14=" Based on data and analysis by S.Fuller. Valid above .380 caliber. Formula: (.0057 * energy / area) + 61.5 ."
fpower15=" Optimum Game Weight - Big game bullets"
fpower16=" For strong jacketed bullets with contolled expansion. By Ed Matunas - formula published in Lyman #47 Reloading Manual. Formula: (velocity^3 * weight^2 * 1.5*10^-12)"
fpower17=" Optimum Game Weight - Frangible bullets "
fpower18=" For frangible bullets. By Ed Matunas - formula published in Lyman #47 Reloading Manual. Formula: (velocity^3 * weight^2 * 5*10^-13)"
fpower19=" Penetration factor, developed by John Wootter. Same as Lott Power Factor EEE1."
fpower20=" Given by Arnold Arms to determine the relative performance of a load/bullet. It already assumes one isn't going to use a more frangible bullet when a stronger jacketed or solid one is required. Values for: varmints 10-30, small big game 30-50, medium big game 50-70, heavy big game 70-100, dangerous game 100-150. Formula: (0.001 * diameter * weight * velocity^2) / 7000 ."
fpower21=" Given by Elmer Keith, Formula: (Velocity * Weight / 7000)."
fpower22=" Described by Gen. Julian S. Hatcher in : Textbook of Pistols and Revolvers, 1935, There he made some corrections to the older RSP's. Formula: (shapefactor * area * momentum)."
fpower23=" Given by P.O. Ackley in the book: Handbook for Shooters and Reloaders, V.I. Formula: (Velocity/100 * Weight/100)."
fpower24= " Greenhill's twist length required "
fpower25= "Described by Julian S. Hatcher in : Hatcher's Notebook, 1962, Formula: (150 * Squareroot(10.9/Specific gravity of bullet material) / length of bullet in calibers = twist length in calibers)."
fpower26="Calibers"
fpower27="Bullet length"

